# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apicomplexa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Diseases caused by *Acanthamoeba* include keratitis and granulomatous amoebic encephalitis (GAE).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The latter is often but not always seen in immunosuppressed patients.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] GAE is caused by the amoebae entering the body through an open wound and then spreading to the brain.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The combination of host immune responses and secreted amoebal proteases causes massive brain swelling resulting in death in about 95% of those infected.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Granulomatous amoebic encephalitis (GAE) is caused by amoebic infection of the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] It is characterized by neurological symptoms including headache, seizures, and mental-status abnormalities.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] These worsen progressively over weeks to months, leading to death in most patients.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Infection is generally associated with underlying conditions such as immunodeficiency, diabetes, malignancies, malnutrition, systemic lupus erythematosus, and alcoholism.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The parasite enters the body through cuts in the skin or by being inhaled into the upper respiratory tract.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The parasite then spreads through the blood into the CNS.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* crosses the blood–brain barrier by means that are not yet understood.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Subsequent invasion of the connective tissue and induction of pro-inflammatory responses leads to neuronal damage that can be fatal within days.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Pure granulomatous lesions are rare in patients with AIDS and other related immunodeficiency states, as the patients do not have adequate numbers of CD+ve T-cells to mount a granulomatous response to *Acanthamoeba* infection in CNS and other organs and tissues.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] A perivascular cuffing with amoebae in necrotic tissue is usual finding in the AIDS and related T-cell immunodeficiency conditions.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Brain biopsy normally reveals severe oedema and hemorrhagic necrosis.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] A patient who has contracted this illness usually displays subacute symptoms, including altered mental status, headaches, fever, neck stiffness, seizures, and focal neurological signs (such as cranial nerve palsies and coma), all leading to death within one week to several months.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Due to the rarity of this parasite and a lack of knowledge, no good diagnoses or treatments for *Acanthamoeba* infection are now known.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* keratitis cases in the past have resolved from a therapy consisting of atropine and some other drugs with no antimicrobial effects.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Recent publications show atropine to interfere with the protist's CHRM1 receptor, causing cell death.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Infection usually mimics that of bacterial leptomeningitis, tuberculous meningitis, or viral encephalitis.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The misdiagnosis often leads to erroneous, ineffective treatment.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] In the case that the *Acanthamoeba* is diagnosed correctly, the current treatments, such as amphotericin B, rifampicin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, ketoconazole, fluconazole, sulfadiazine, or albendazole, are only tentatively successful.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Correct and timely diagnosis, as well as improved treatment methods and an understanding of the parasite, are important factors in improving the outcome of infection by *Acanthamoeba*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] A paper published in 2013 has shown substantial effects of some FDA-approved drugs with an *in vitro* kill rate above 90%.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] These results were *in vitro* effects, but as the drugs are already approved, human infections can be targeted after dose calculations in clinical trials done with these diverse groups of drugs.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] When present in the eye, *Acanthamoeba* strains can cause acanthamoebic keratitis, which may lead to corneal ulcers or even blindness.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] This condition occurs most often among contact lens wearers who do not properly disinfect their lenses, exacerbated by a failure to wash hands prior to handling the lenses.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Multipurpose contact lens solutions are largely ineffective against *Acanthamoeba*, whereas hydrogen peroxide-based solutions have good disinfection characteristics.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The first cure of a corneal infection was achieved in 1985 at Moorfields Eye Hospital.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] In May 2007, Advanced Medical Optics, manufacturer of Complete Moisture Plus Contact Lens Solution products, issued a voluntary recall of their Complete Moisture Plus solutions.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The fear was that contact lens wearers who used their solution were at higher risk of acanthamoebic keratitis than contact lens wearers who used other solutions.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The manufacturer recalled the product after the Centers for Disease Control in the United States found that 21 people had possibly received an *Acanthamoeba* infection after using Complete Moisture Plus in the month prior to diagnosis.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Several species of bacteria that can cause human disease are also able to infect and replicate within *Acanthamoeba* species.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] These include *Legionella pneumophila*, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, and some strains of *Escherichia coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] For some of these bacteria, replication inside *Acanthamoeba* has been associated with enhanced growth in macrophages, and increased resistance to some antibiotics.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Furthermore, due to the high prevalence of *Acanthamoeba* in the environment, these amoebae have been proposed to serve as an environmental reservoir for some human pathogens.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] This species is able to lyse bacteria and produce a wide range of enzymes, such as cellulases or chitinases, and probably contributes to the breakdown of organic matter in soil, contributing to the microbial loop.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] In addition, *Acanthamoeba* has been used extensively to understand the molecular biology of cell motility and cancer cell dormancy by in-depth exploration of the process of encystation.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The recently available *Acanthamoeba* genome sequence revealed several orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] This finding suggests that *Acanthamoeba* is capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Owing to its ease and economy of cultivation, the Neff strain of *A. castellanii*, discovered in a pond in Golden Gate Park in the 1960s, has been effectively used as a classic model organism in the field of cell biology.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] From just 30 L of simple medium inoculated with *A. castellanii*, about 1 kg of cells can be obtained after several days of aerated culture at room temperature.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Pioneered in the laboratory of Edward D.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Korn at the National Institutes of Health (NIH), many important biological molecules have been discovered and their pathways elucidated using the *Acanthamoeba* model.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* also has served as a model to study the evolution of certain G-proteins.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] This unicellular eukaryote expresses few GPCRs over its cell membrane that serve vital role for the microorganism, structural homology bioinformatics tools have been used to show the presence of a homolog of human M1-muscarinic receptor in *A. castellanii*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Blocking these muscarinic receptors in past studies has proven to be amoebicidal in Acanthamoeba spp.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] More recently, voltage-gated calcium channels in *Acanthamoeba* spp.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] (CavAc) have been reported to have similarities with human voltage-gated calcium channels such as TPC-1 and L-type calcium channels and respond to Ca-channel blockers such as loperamide.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] This model microbe has been studied to understand complex neurodegenerative states including Alzheimer's disease.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Scientists have isolated a neurotransmitter acetylcholine in *Acanthamoeba* and the enzymatic machinery needed for its synthesis.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] The giant viruses *Mimivirus, Megavirus*, and *Pandoravirus* infect *Acanthamoeba*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Members of the genus *Acanthamoeba* are unusual in serving as hosts for a variety of giant viruses (that have more than 1000 protein-coding genes; for instance, *Pandoravirus*, which has about 2500 protein-coding genes in its genome).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Below is a list of described species of *Acanthamoeba*, with sequence types noted where known.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] Species that have been identified in diseased patients are marked with *.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] From the Greek ἄκανθα *akantha* (spike/thorn), which was added before "amoeba" (change) to describe this organism as having a spine-like structure (**acanthopodia**).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthamoeba] This organism is now well known as **Acanthamoeba**, an amphizoic, opportunistic, and nonopportunistic protozoan protist widely distributed in the environment.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:apicomplexa/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] The taxonomy of these organisms has been one of some controversy.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] Weylon in 1926 grouped many of these genera into the genus *Babesia* - given what is now known about these genera this was probably an error.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] Agreement on the organisation of these genera probably cannot be regarded as being settled.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] These are minute rounded or pyriform parasites found within erythrocytes, or other circulating or endothelial cells of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] The parasites reproduce by merogony without oocysts or spores.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] The apical complex has a polar ring and rhoptries.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] A conoid is lacking and most species lack the associated pellicular microtubules.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] The trophozoite stage is separated from erythrocyte by single membrane (in the other groups there usually 2 or more).
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] These are agents of piroplasmosis *sensu stricto*.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] The species have been placed into two families.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] This family excludes species that undergo schizogony in lymphocytes before parasitizing erythrocytes. these species have been placed in the genus *Theileria*.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] Species in this family have rhoptries, a polar ring and subpellicular tubules in its apical complex.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] With the exception of the genus *Tunetella* which infects tortoises, species in this family infect in warm-blooded vertebrates and are transmitted by ticks.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] This family includes species that infect marine animals.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] A notable exception is the genus *Serpentoplasma* which infects reptiles.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] Very little is known about most of these genera.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] The genus *Nephromyces* may also belong to this family.
[src:apicomplexa/achromatorida] These are parasites of erythrocytes and diverse white blood cells with sexual reproduction by exoerythrocytic or by exo- and endoerythrocytic schizogony.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:apicomplexa/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:apicomplexa/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:apicomplexa/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:apicomplexa/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:apicomplexa/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:apicomplexa/aconoidasida] The **Aconoidasida** are a class of apicomplexan parasites described by Mehlhorn *et al* in 1980.
[src:apicomplexa/aconoidasida] Organisms in this class bear a tip at one end of their outer membrane.
[src:apicomplexa/aconoidasida] This apical complex includes vesicles called rhoptries and micronemes, which open at the anterior of the cell.
[src:apicomplexa/aconoidasida] These secrete enzymes that allow the parasite to enter other cells.
[src:apicomplexa/aconoidasida] The tip is surrounded by a band of microtubules, called the polar ring.
[src:apicomplexa/aconoidasida] As the name indicates, Aconoidasida (from Greek: negative prefix *a-* = "lacking") lack a conoid (they do have one only during the ookinete stage) in contrast to the class Conoidasida which have one throughout their life cycle.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The **Apicomplexa** (also called **Apicomplexia**; single: **apicomplexan**) are organisms of a large phylum of mainly parasitic alveolates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Most possess a unique form of organelle structure that comprises a type of non-photosynthetic plastid called an apicoplast—with an apical complex membrane.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The organelle's apical shape is an adaptation that the apicomplexan applies in penetrating a host cell.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Apicomplexa are unicellular and spore-forming.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Most are obligate endoparasites of animals, except *Nephromyces*, a symbiont in marine animals, originally classified as a chytrid fungus.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Motile structures such as flagella or pseudopods are present only in certain gamete stages.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Apicomplexa are a diverse group that includes organisms such as the coccidia, gregarines, piroplasms, haemogregarines, and plasmodia.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The name Apicomplexa derives from two Latin words—*apex* (top) and *complexus* (infolds)—for the set of organelles in the sporozoite.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Apicomplexa comprise the bulk of what used to be called the **Sporozoa**, a group of parasitic protozoans, in general without flagella, cilia, or pseudopods.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Most of the Apicomplexa can use gliding motility, that uses adhesions and small static myosin motors.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The other main lines of this obsolete grouping were the Ascetosporea (a group of Rhizaria), the Myxozoa (highly derived cnidarian animals), and the Microsporidia (derived from fungi).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Sometimes, the name Sporozoa is taken as a synonym for the Apicomplexa, or occasionally as a subset.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The phylum Apicomplexa contains all eukaryotes with a group of structures and organelles collectively termed the apical complex.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This complex consists of structural components and secretory organelles required for invasion of host cells during the parasitic stages of the Apicomplexan life cycle.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Apicomplexa have complex life cycles, involving several stages and typically undergoing both asexual and sexual replication.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] All Apicomplexa are obligate parasites for some portion of their life cycle, with some parasitizing two separate hosts for their asexual and sexual stages.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Besides the conserved apical complex, Apicomplexa are morphologically diverse.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Different organisms within Apicomplexa, as well as different life stages for a given apicomplexan, can vary substantially in size, shape, and subcellular structure.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Like other eukaryotes, Apicomplexa have a nucleus, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi complex.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Apicomplexa generally have a single mitochondrion, as well as another endosymbiont-derived organelle called the apicoplast which maintains a separate 35 kilobase circular genome (with the exception of *Cryptosporidium* species and *Gregarina niphandrodes* which lack an apicoplast).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] All members of this phylum have an infectious stage—the sporozoite—which possesses three distinct structures in an apical complex.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The apical complex consists of a set of spirally arranged microtubules (the conoid), a secretory body (the rhoptry) and one or more polar rings.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Additional slender electron-dense secretory bodies (micronemes) surrounded by one or two polar rings may also be present.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This structure gives the phylum its name.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] A further group of spherical organelles is distributed throughout the cell rather than being localized at the apical complex and are known as the dense granules.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] These typically have a mean diameter around 0.7 μm.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Secretion of the dense-granule content takes place after parasite invasion and localization within the parasitophorous vacuole and persists for several minutes.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Apicomplexans have a unique gliding capability which enables them to cross through tissues and enter and leave their host cells.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This gliding ability is made possible by the use of adhesions and small static myosin motors.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Other features common to this phylum are a lack of cilia, sexual reproduction, use of micropores for feeding, and the production of oocysts containing sporozoites as the infective form.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Transposons appear to be rare in this phylum, but have been identified in the genera *Ascogregarina* and *Eimeria*.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Most members have a complex lifecycle, involving both asexual and sexual reproduction.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Typically, a host is infected via an active invasion by the parasites (similar to entosis), which divide to produce sporozoites that enter its cells.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Eventually, the cells burst, releasing merozoites, which infect new cells.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This may occur several times, until gamonts are produced, forming gametes that fuse to create new cysts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Many variations occur on this basic pattern, however, and many Apicomplexa have more than one host.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The apical complex includes vesicles called rhoptries and micronemes, which open at the anterior of the cell.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The tip is surrounded by a band of microtubules, called the polar ring, and among the Conoidasida is also a funnel of tubulin proteins called the conoid.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Over the rest of the cell, except for a diminished mouth called the micropore, the membrane is supported by vesicles called alveoli, forming a semirigid pellicle.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The presence of alveoli and other traits place the Apicomplexa among a group called the alveolates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Several related flagellates, such as *Perkinsus* and *Colpodella*, have structures similar to the polar ring and were formerly included here, but most appear to be closer relatives of the dinoflagellates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] They are probably similar to the common ancestor of the two groups.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Another similarity is that many apicomplexan cells contain a single plastid, called the apicoplast, surrounded by either three or four membranes.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Its functions are thought to include tasks such as lipid and heme biosynthesis, and it appears to be necessary for survival.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In general, plastids are considered to have a common origin with the chloroplasts of dinoflagellates, and evidence points to an origin from red algae rather than green.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Within this phylum are four groups — coccidians, gregarines, haemosporidians (or haematozoans, including in addition piroplasms), and marosporidians.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The coccidians and haematozoans appear to be relatively closely related.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The gregarines are generally parasites of annelids, arthropods, and molluscs.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] They are often found in the guts of their hosts, but may invade the other tissues.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In the typical gregarine lifecycle, a trophozoite develops within a host cell into a schizont.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This then divides into a number of merozoites by schizogony.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The merozoites are released by lysing the host cell, which in turn invade other cells.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] At some point in the apicomplexan lifecycle, gametocytes are formed.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] These are released by lysis of the host cells, which group together.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The gametes fuse with another to form oocysts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The oocysts leave the host to be taken up by a new host.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In general, coccidians are parasites of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Like gregarines, they are commonly parasites of the epithelial cells of the gut, but may infect other tissues.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The coccidian lifecycle involves merogony, gametogony, and sporogony.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] While similar to that of the gregarines it differs in zygote formation.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Some trophozoites enlarge and become macrogamete, whereas others divide repeatedly to form microgametes (anisogamy).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The microgametes are motile and must reach the macrogamete to fertilize it.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The fertilized macrogamete forms a zygote that in its turn forms an oocyst that is normally released from the body.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Syzygy, when it occurs, involves markedly anisogamous gametes.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The lifecycle is typically haploid, with the only diploid stage occurring in the zygote, which is normally short-lived.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The main difference between the coccidians and the gregarines is in the gamonts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In the coccidia, these are small, intracellular, and without epimerites or mucrons.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In the gregarines, these are large, extracellular, and possess epimerites or mucrons.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] A second difference between the coccidia and the gregarines also lies in the gamonts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In the coccidians, a single gamont becomes a macrogametocyte, whereas in the gregarines, the gamonts give rise to multiple gametocytes.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Haemosporidia have more complex lifecycles that alternate between an arthropod and a vertebrate host.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The trophozoite parasitises erythrocytes or other tissues in the vertebrate host.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Microgametes and macrogametes are always found in the blood.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The gametes are taken up by the insect vector during a blood meal.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The microgametes migrate within the gut of the insect vector and fuse with the macrogametes.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The fertilized macrogamete now becomes an ookinete, which penetrates the body of the vector.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The ookinete then transforms into an oocyst and divides initially by meiosis and then by mitosis (haplontic lifecycle) to give rise to the sporozoites.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The sporozoites escape from the oocyst and migrate within the body of the vector to the salivary glands where they are injected into the new vertebrate host when the insect vector feeds again.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The class Marosporida Mathur, Kristmundsson, Gestal, Freeman, and Keeling 2020 is a newly recognized lineage of apicomplexans that is sister to the Coccidia and Hematozoa.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] It is defined as a phylogenetic clade containing *Aggregata octopiana* Frenzel 1885, *Merocystis kathae* Dakin, 1911 (both Aggregatidae, originally coccidians), *Rhytidocystis* sp.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] 2019 (Rhytidocystidae Levine, 1979, originally coccidians, Agamococcidiorida), and *Margolisiella islandica* Kristmundsson et al.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] 2011 (closely related to Rhytidocystidae).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Marosporida infect marine invertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Members of this clade retain plastid genomes and the canonical apicomplexan plastid metabolism.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] However, marosporidians have the most reduced apicoplast genomes sequenced to date, lack canonical plastidial RNA polymerase and so provide new insights into reductive organelle evolution.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Many of the apicomplexan parasites are important pathogens of humans and domestic animals.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In contrast to bacterial pathogens, these apicomplexan parasites are eukaryotic and share many metabolic pathways with their animal hosts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This makes therapeutic target development extremely difficult – a drug that harms an apicomplexan parasite is also likely to harm its human host.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] At present, no effective vaccines are available for most diseases caused by these parasites.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Biomedical research on these parasites is challenging because it is often difficult, if not impossible, to maintain live parasite cultures in the laboratory and to genetically manipulate these organisms.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] In recent years, several of the apicomplexan species have been selected for genome sequencing.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The availability of genome sequences provides a new opportunity for scientists to learn more about the evolution and biochemical capacity of these parasites.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The predominant source of this genomic information is the EuPathDB family of websites, which currently provides specialised services for *Plasmodium* species (PlasmoDB), coccidians (ToxoDB), piroplasms (PiroplasmaDB), and *Cryptosporidium* species (CryptoDB).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] One possible target for drugs is the plastid, and in fact existing drugs such as tetracyclines, which are effective against apicomplexans, seem to operate against the plastid.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Many Coccidiomorpha have an intermediate host, as well as a definitive host, and the evolution of hosts proceeded in different ways and at different times in these groups.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] For most coccidiomorphs, the original host has remained the definitive host and the newly acquired host(s) acted as intermediate hosts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Similar strategies to increase the likelihood of transmission have evolved in multiple genera.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Polyenergid oocysts and tissue cysts are found in representatives of the orders Protococcidiorida and Eimeriida.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Hypnozoites are found in *Karyolysus lacerate* and most species of *Plasmodium*; transovarial transmission of parasites occurs in lifecycles of *Karyolysus* and *Babesia*.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Horizontal gene transfer appears to have occurred early on in this phylum's evolution with the transfer of a histone H4 lysine 20 (H4K20) modifier, KMT5A (Set8), from an animal host to the ancestor of apicomplexans.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] A second gene—H3K36 methyltransferase (Ashr3 in plants)—may have also been horizontally transferred.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Within the Adelorina are species that infect invertebrates and others that infect vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Eimeriorina—the largest suborder in this phylum—the lifecycle involves both sexual and asexual stages.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The asexual stages reproduce by schizogony.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The male gametocyte produces a large number of gametes and the zygote gives rise to an oocyst, which is the infective stage.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The majority are monoxenous (infect one host only), but a few are heteroxenous (lifecycle involves two or more hosts).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The number of families in this later suborder is debated, with the number of families being between one and 20 depending on the authority and the number of genera being between 19 and 25.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The first Apicomplexa protozoan was seen by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek, who in 1674 saw probably oocysts of *Eimeria stiedae* in the gall bladder of a rabbit.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The first species of the phylum to be described, *Gregarina ovata*, in earwigs' intestines, was named by Dufour in 1828.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] He thought that they were a peculiar group related to the trematodes, at that time included in Vermes.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Since then, many more have been identified and named.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] During 1826–1850, 41 species and six genera of Apicomplexa were named.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The older taxon Sporozoa, included in Protozoa, was created by Leuckart in 1879 and adopted by Bütschli in 1880.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Through history, it grouped with the current Apicomplexa many unrelated groups.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] For example, Kudo (1954) included in the Sporozoa species of the Ascetosporea (Rhizaria), Microsporidia (Fungi), Myxozoa (Animalia), and *Helicosporidium* (Chlorophyta), while Zierdt (1978) included the genus *Blastocystis* (Stramenopiles).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] *Dermocystidium* was also thought to be sporozoan.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Not all of these groups had spores, but all were parasitic.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] If they had cell walls, they also could be included in plant kingdom between bacteria or yeasts.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Sporozoa is no longer regarded as biologically valid and its use is discouraged, although some authors still use it as a synonym for the Apicomplexa.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] More recently, other groups were excluded from Apicomplexa, e.g., *Perkinsus* and *Colpodella* (now in Protalveolata).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The field of classifying Apicomplexa is in flux and classification has changed throughout the years since it was formally named in 1970.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] By 1987, a comprehensive survey of the phylum was completed: in all, 4516 species and 339 genera had been named.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Although considerable revision of this phylum has been done (the order Haemosporidia now has 17 genera rather than 9), these numbers are probably still approximately correct.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Jacques Euzéby in 1988 created a new class Haemosporidiasina by merging subclass Piroplasmasina and suborder Haemospororina.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The division into Achromatorida and Chromatorida, although proposed on morphological grounds, may have a biological basis, as the ability to store haemozoin appears to have evolved only once.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The adeleorins are one-host parasites of invertebrates or vertebrates, or two-host parasites that alternately infect haematophagous (blood-feeding) invertebrates and the blood of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The eimeriorins are a diverse group that includes one host species of invertebrates, two-host species of invertebrates, one-host species of vertebrates and two-host species of vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The eimeriorins are frequently called the coccidia.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This term is often used to include the adeleorins.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Haemospororins, often known as the malaria parasites, are two-host Apicomplexa that parasitize blood-feeding dipteran flies and the blood of various tetrapod vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Piroplasms where all the species included are two-host parasites infecting ticks and vertebrates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Perkins et al. proposed the following scheme.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Macrogamete and microgamete develop separately.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Heteroxenous: alternates between vertebrate host (in which merogony occurs) and invertebrate host (in which sporogony occurs).
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Usually blood parasites, transmitted by blood-sucking insects.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The name Protospiromonadida has been proposed for the common ancestor of the Gregarinomorpha and Coccidiomorpha.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Another group of organisms that belong in this taxon are the corallicolids.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] These are found in coral reef gastric cavities.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Their relationship to the others in this phylum has yet to be established.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Another genus has been identified - *Nephromyces* - which appears to be a sister taxon to the Hematozoa.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This genus is found in the renal sac of molgulid ascidian tunicates.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Members of this phylum, except for the photosynthetic chromerids, are parasitic and evolved from a free-living ancestor.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] This lifestyle is presumed to have evolved at the time of the divergence of dinoflagellates and apicomplexans.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Further evolution of this phylum has been estimated to have occurred about 800 million years ago.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The oldest extant clade is thought to be the archigregarines.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] These phylogenetic relations have rarely been studied at the subclass level.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Haemosporidia are related to the gregarines, and the piroplasms and coccidians are sister groups.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] The Haemosporidia and the Piroplasma appear to be sister clades, and are more closely related to the coccidians than to the gregarines.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] Marosporida is a sister group to Coccidiomorphea.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] 2015 presents a somewhat different phylogeny, supporting the work of others showing multiple events of plastids losing photosynthesis.
[src:apicomplexa/apicomplexa] More importantly this work provides the first phylogenetic evidence that there have also been multiple events of plastids becoming genome-free.
